{
  "text": "Remark 2.2. This result resembles the Serre-Stark theorem (see [CITATION_1] ) which states that every scalar valued modular form of weight 1/2 is a linear combination of elementary theta functions \u03b8 \u03c8,m (\u03c4 ) = n\u2208Z \u03c8(n)n \u03bd q mn 2 , where \u03bd = 0 and \u03c8 is a primitive Dirichlet character with \u03c8(\u22121) = 1 (for \u03bd = 1 and \u03c8(\u22121) = \u22121 the theta function \u03b8 \u03c8,m is a cusp form of weight 3/2). If we split \u03b8 \u03c8,m (\u03c4 ) = r(2d) \u03c8(r) n\u2261r(2d) n \u03bd q mn 2 , where d is the conductor of \u03c8, we see that the inner sums are just the components of a vector valued unary theta function. Hence, many of the results of the present work, which are formulated for vector valued unary theta functions, immediatly imply the corresponding statements for the classical scalar valued theta functions.",
  "correct_citation": {
    "[CITATION_1]": "116432445"
  },
  "bib_entries": {
    "116432445": {
      "title": "Modular forms of weight 1/2",
      "abstract": "We will construct \u03b8-series of weight 1/2 and 3/2 for some congruence subgroups of SL(2,\u2124) by taking appropriate coefficients of the representation \\( \\mathop{R}\\limits^{\\sim } \\) of SL(2;\u211d), illustrating the method sketched in 2.3. Our method will be the following: ::: ::: 1) ::: ::: Analyze the possible lowest weight vectors in the Shale-Weil representation \\( \\mathop{R}\\limits^{\\sim } \\) of \\( \\mathop{G}\\limits^{\\sim } \\) ::: ::: ::: ::: ::: 2) ::: ::: For a given congruence subgroup \u0393 of SL(2,\u2124), produce some semi-invariant linear functionals under \u0393, using the model H = H(r, x) of the representation W."
